MSBR 70200: In-class Exercise Hypothesis Testing

Name: Jack



The following exercises can be directly performed in Radiant or in a regular R environment (in RStudio). Do recognize that you should modify R code from Radiant to run in RStudio. You can choose either way to complete the exercise.


1. Advertising Agency

An advertising agency has been hired by a network to determine an optimal balance of commercials for its daytime soap opera audience. The agency has designed a plan under the assumption that 80% of its audience are women. The agency would consider reworking its plan if the proportion of women is significantly lower than 80%.

Use advertising dataset after loading advertising.rda

1-1. Write your hypothesis

Either in English or in Math

  • The null hypothesis: p >= 0.8
  • The alternative hypothesis: p < 0.8

1-2. Hypothesis Testing R Code and Result

result <- single_prop(
  advertising, 
  var = "gender", 
  lev = "female", 
  comp_value = 0.8, 
  alternative = "less"
)
summary(result)
Single proportion test (binomial exact)
Data      : advertising 
Variable  : gender 
Level     : female in gender 
Confidence: 0.95 
Null hyp. : the proportion of female in gender = 0.8 
Alt. hyp. : the proportion of female in gender < 0.8 

     p  ns   n n_missing    sd    se    me
 0.730 292 400         0 0.444 0.022 0.044

   diff  ns p.value    0%   95%    
 -0.070 292  < .001 0.000 0.766 ***

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
plot(result, plots = "bar", custom = FALSE)


1-3. Conclusion

Since p-value is less than .001, we reject the null hypothesis at 5% significant level and assumes that prop of woman is less than 0.8



2. Diamond Price

We want to test if the population mean of diamond price is $4,000.

Use diamonds dataset.

2-1. Write your hypothesis

Either in English or in Math

  • The null hypothesis: mu = 4000
  • The alternative hypothesis: mu != 4000

2-2. Hypothesis Testing R Code and Result

result <- single_mean(
  diamonds, 
  var = "price", 
  comp_value = 4000, 
  conf_lev = 0.85
)
summary(result)
Single mean test
Data      : diamonds 
Variable  : price 
Confidence: 0.85 
Null hyp. : the mean of price = 4000 
Alt. hyp. : the mean of price is not equal to 4000 

      mean     n n_missing        sd     se      me
 3,907.186 3,000         0 3,956.915 72.243 104.023

    diff     se t.value p.value   df     7.5%    92.5%  
 -92.814 72.243  -1.285   0.199 2999 3803.163 4011.209  

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
plot(result, plots = "hist", custom = FALSE)


2-3. Conclusion

Since p-value is bigger than 1%, we do not reject the null hypothesis Thus, we assume that the mean of the diamond price is is not different from 4000.



3. Diamond Price per Cut

We want to test if the ‘fair’ cut diamond price is different from the ‘premium’ cut diamond price.

Use diamonds dataset.

3-1. Write your hypothesis

Either in English or in Math

  • The null hypothesis: mu_fair is equal to mu_premium
  • The alternative hypothesis: mu_fair is not equal to mu_premium

3-2. Hypothesis Testing R Code and Result

result <- compare_means(
  diamonds, 
  var1 = "cut", 
  var2 = "price", 
  comb = "Fair:Premium"
)
summary(result, show = FALSE)
Pairwise mean comparisons (t-test)
Data      : diamonds 
Variables : cut, price 
Samples   : independent 
Confidence: 0.95 
Adjustment: None 

       cut      mean     n n_missing        sd      se      me
      Fair 4,505.238   101         0 3,749.540 373.093 740.206
      Good 4,130.433   275         0 3,730.354 224.949 442.848
 Very Good 3,959.916   677         0 3,895.899 149.732 293.995
   Premium 4,369.409   771         0 4,236.977 152.591 299.544
     Ideal 3,470.224 1,176         0 3,827.423 111.610 218.977

 Null hyp.        Alt. hyp.                   diff    p.value  
 Fair = Premium   Fair not equal to Premium   135.829 0.737    

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
plot(result, plots = "scatter", custom = FALSE)


3-3. Conclusion


Since p-value is higher than 1%, we do not reject the null hypothesis at 1% significant level. Thus, we assume that the mean of fair cut price is not different from the mean of premium cut price.
